  "prompt": "What's the difference between \u51e0 and \u591a\u5c11 in the following sentences?",
  "response": "In Mandarin Chinese, both \"\u51e0\" (j\u01d0) and \"\u591a\u5c11\" (du\u014dshao) can translate to \"how many\" or \"how much\" in English, but they are used in different contexts.\n\n1. **\u51e0 (j\u01d0)**: \n   - \"\u51e0\" is often used to ask about a small, specific number or quantity. It is typically used when the speaker expects the answer to be a number that is relatively small and within a certain range, usually less than 10. \n   - Example: \n     - \u4f60\u6709\u51e0\u4e2a\u82f9\u679c\uff1f(N\u01d0 y\u01d2u j\u01d0 g\u00e8 p\u00ednggu\u01d2?) - \"How many apples do you have?\" (Expecting a small number)\n\n2. **\u591a\u5c11 (du\u014dshao)**:\n   - \"\u591a\u5c11,\" on the other hand, is used when asking about larger quantities or when the range of possible answers is not limited. It can refer to both countable and uncountable nouns.\n   - Example: \n     - \u4f60\u82b1\u4e86\u591a\u5c11\u94b1\uff1f(N\u01d0 hu\u0101le du\u014dshao qi\u00e1n?) - \"How much money did you spend?\" (Expecting a larger or indefinite amount)\n\nIn summary, use \"\u51e0\" when referring to smaller, specific counts and \"\u591a\u5c11\" when the quantity is more extensive or indefinite.",
